DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(78)90004-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387878900044
AB  - This paper attempts to show that because the production function in manufacturing industries is nonhomothetic and relative factor prices vary across countries, the average size of plants is positively associated not only with the level of economic development but also with physical capital intensity. The measures of average size by employment is derived for a large number of industries from the parameters of the fifted lognormal distribution. Nonwage value added per employee is deployed as a proxy for physical capital intensity. The posited hypothesis are tested for a sample of 23 countries at various levels of development.
